programme.title: Sex Actually with Alice Levine
programme.desc: Alice travels from London to Washington, DC meeting people who are entering relationships with multiple partners in a bid for more sex and a deeper connection, including a 20-person polycule - a group of open-minded lovers who have created an ever-evolving support system through their intertwined sex lives. programme.title: First Dates Hotel
programme.desc: The final group of singletons check in searching for their perfect partners. programme.title: The Dog House
programme.desc: Woodgreen animal charity staff set about matching their homeless dogs with more prospective owners. programme.title: The Piano
programme.desc: The hunt for outstanding amateur pianists continues in Glasgow Central Station with impromptu performances from a local jazz legend, an 86 year-old father of 11, a YouTube star and a boogie woogie biker who believes music is in her DNA. programme.title: Come Dine with Me
programme.desc: This competition takes place in and around Liverpool, where the first to host is 41-year-old taxi business owner Rob, who plans a Scouse themed evening. The guests he is hoping to impress are 23-year-old fitness fanatic Toria, 44-year-old property developer Christine, 40-year-old South African business woman Sam, and 20-year-old student Inzy.

programme.title: Come Dine with Me
programme.desc: It is night two in Liverpool, and the turn of businesswoman Sam to try and impress with her South-African-themed evening, though her food is a bit hit and miss.

programme.title: Come Dine with Me
programme.desc: Gym worker Toria hosts the third party in Liverpool, and hopes a kissing game around the dinner table, along with her flaky flapjacks, will be enough to secure the £1,000 prize.

programme.title: Come Dine with Me
programme.desc: Undergraduate Inzy is the fourth host in Liverpool, and he is on a mission to prove students really can cook. The flirting between him and Toria continues, but will he allow love to stand in way of the competition?.

programme.title: Come Dine with Me
programme.desc: In Liverpool, property developer Christine plans to wow her guests with a Spanish holiday-themed dinner party. However, the mood is rather more feisty than fiesta as on-going tensions finally come to a head and it's not long before the honesty - and the sparks - begin to fly.

programme.title: A Place in the Sun
programme.desc: Tina Watkins has long struggled to get on the housing ladder in the UK. Now, she has decided to make the most of the incredibly good value property in Spain's Granada province and buy her first-ever home. With her best friend Jamie along to help, Jasmine Harman shows Tina just how far her £19,000 budget will stretch.

programme.title: A Place in the Sun
programme.desc: Rick and Inge cannot wait to fulfill their dream of buying a holiday home in Tala in western Cyprus, near the beautiful beaches of Coral Bay. The cat-crazy couple ask Jean Johansson to help them find a detached villa for their budget of £260,000, with plenty of space for a feline family and a 'man cave' for Rick's DIY.

programme.title: A New Life in the Sun: Where Are They Now?
programme.desc: Catching up with a father and daughter horse riding duo in Italy, who need to think on their feet if they are to survive another hot Italian summer. Marc and Natalia's paddleboarding business in Spain branches out into new territory, and on the Costa Blanca, Dan, Rik and Rex have their dreams of owning a gin distillery dashed.

programme.title: Come Dine with Me
programme.desc: Ptol Slattery hosts the first dinner party in Winchester, Hampshire, but his menu of seared scallops, lamb steak with baby new potatoes followed by chocolate mousse leaves his guests - waitress Patrician Pearson, DJ Francis Leigh, care-home worker Georgia Groves and estate agent William Tilsley - underwhelmed.

programme.title: Come Dine with Me
programme.desc: DJ Francis Leigh hosts the next dinner party in Winchester, hoping to dazzle his guests with his sunburnt chicken curry, a Thai meal with a twist and a dessert simply called 'sticky.' The entertainment for the night proves to be weird and wonderful as he dons a tutu and fur coat to serve the main course.

programme.title: Come Dine with Me
programme.desc: Waitress Patricia Pearson hosts the next party in Winchester, but the decision to write her menu in Spanish causes confusion for one guest who mistakes lamb for llama. The Peruvian-themed feast is followed by a rendition of the country's national anthem and a traditional dance involving a candle and a donkey's jaw.

programme.title: Come Dine with Me
programme.desc: On the fourth night of the competition in Winchester, Georgia Groves plans a black-tie evening complete with a red carpet, posh frocks and a spray-tan booth. It appears to be going well until Patricia Pearson reveals what she thinks of Ptol Slattery and his wine antics.

programme.title: Come Dine with Me
programme.desc: Estate agent William Tilsley throws one last dinner party as a week of competitions in Winchester, Hampshire, draws to a close. The host plans to offer his guests a vegetarian menu, with a blind food-tasting game providing the evening's entertainment. As the night draws to a close, one of the competitors rises above the rest to become the winner.

programme.title: A Place in the Sun
programme.desc: Jasmine Harman heads to the Charente region of France to help a couple find a holiday home to enjoy with their children and grandchildren. For their budget of £250,000, Sarah and Greg would like a traditional French cottage or converted barn with four bedrooms in a rural location.

programme.title: Emergency Helicopter Medics
programme.desc: The air ambulance teams are called out to help Dennis, who's suffering a heart attack. A spin on her bike has catastrophic consequences for Carolyn. Plus, there's a dramatic night-time car crash in Norfolk.

programme.title: Law & Order: Special Victims Unit

programme.title: Law & Order: Special Victims Unit

programme.title: Romancing the Stone: The Golden Ages of British Sculpture
programme.desc: Alastair Sooke examines sculpture in the 20th century, an era of innovation, scandal and creativity. He examines the artistic revolution spearheaded by Eric Gill and Jacob Epstein, which paved the way for the work of Gilbert & George and Damien Hirst. He also explores the art form's rise in popularity, from First World War memorials to the landmark work of Antony Gormley and Rachel Whiteread.

programme.title: Great British Railway Journeys
programme.desc: Michael Portillo explores the Britain of the 1930s as he sets out on another adventure. Beginning just outside Newcastle in Jarrow, Michael uncovers the desperation that led 200 men to march 300 miles to Westminster in order to petition the government for work. The first leg of his journey ends Spennymoor, Co Durham, where he meets the son of a miner who became one of the most famous 20th-century artists of the region.

programme.title: Villages by the Sea
programme.desc: Archaeologist Ben Robinson uncovers the secrets of Thorpeness in Suffolk, the first purpose-built seaside village in the UK. The ingenuity of amenities such as the hand-dug lake, country club and inland housing were the unique vision of Glencairn Stuart Ogilvie. Hamish Ogilvie helps Ben to understand his great-grandfather's vision, stemming from theatrical inspiration.

programme.title: Archaeology: A Secret History
programme.desc: Richard Miles charts the history of archaeological breakthroughs in a mission to understand the ancient past. In the first programme, he explores how the profession began by trying to prove a biblical truth.

programme.title: Art of France
programme.desc: Andrew Graham-Dixon explores how art in France took a dramatic turn after the Revolution ushered in a bold new world of artists including Jacques-Louis David and Theodore Gericault.

programme.title: Great British Railway Journeys
programme.desc: Michael Portillo is in Northumbria en route to the Highlands, heading to Kielder Forest to discover what lay behind a national initiative to plant one of the largest manmade woodlands in Europe. Crossing the border to Scotland, Michael arrives in the weaving town of Hawick to visit Lovat Mill, where, in the 1930s, tweed was big business, and also goes to the movies, sitting in the front stalls at the Dominion cinema in Morningside.

programme.title: Villages by the Sea
programme.desc: Archaeologist Ben Robinson visits Alnmouth, Northumberland, which was founded in the mid-12th century after the barons of nearby Alnwick obtained a charter from King John to build a new village. It had a market and a small port and the village flourished - so much so that by the mid-1700s, Alnmouth's grain export started to play an integral role in feeding the growing English population.

programme.title: As Time Goes By

programme.title: The Mistress

programme.title: A History of Britain by Simon Schama
programme.desc: Simon Schama charts the dramatic story of the political and religious upheavals in Britain following the death of Charles I. Republican leader Oliver Cromwell envisaged a godly kingdom, while Charles II restored the lustre of the monarchy. Subsequent anti-Catholicism during the brief reign of James II led to a pivotal uprising which would transform the country for ever.

programme.title: Newsround
programme.desc: The war in Ukraine is the biggest in Europe since World War II. Millions of children have been forced to leave their homes to escape the fighting, but many either others couldn’t or didn’t. Hearing from just some of those who are living through war, this film lets the children caught in the conflict tell their stories in their own words. Covering fear, loss, strength and hope, they detail the life-changing events of the war and the impact it is having on their day-to-day life. They share their experiences of surviving attacks from the air, being forced to live for weeks at a time in bomb shelters, and their towns and villages becoming occupied by Russian soldiers. Ricky Boleto finds out how the children are coping with living in a country at war..

programme.title: Newsround
programme.desc: The war in Ukraine is the biggest in Europe since World War II. Millions of children have been forced to leave their homes to escape the fighting, but many either others couldn’t or didn’t. Hearing from just some of those who are living through war, this film lets the children caught in the conflict tell their stories in their own words. Covering fear, loss, strength and hope, they detail the life-changing events of the war and the impact it is having on their day-to-day life. They share their experiences of surviving attacks from the air, being forced to live for weeks at a time in bomb shelters, and their towns and villages becoming occupied by Russian soldiers. Ricky Boleto finds out how the children are coping with living in a country at war..

programme.title: Countryfile
programme.desc: Celebrating the 70th anniversary of the first recorded summit of the highest point on earth, Mount Everest, Ellie Harrison heads to Kettering and one of the world's most advanced materials research facilities to put outdoor gear - and herself - to the test. As well as getting to grips with a pair of expedition boots that made it to the top of the world, how will Ellie bear up in a cold chamber where the mercury can hit -40 degrees centigrade? Ellie also dips into the Countryfile archive to remember some pretty bracing encounters with the worst the weather can hurl at people.

programme.title: Dragons' Den
programme.desc: Entrepreneurs Peter Jones, Deborah Meaden, Touker Suleyman, Sara Davies and Steven Bartlett encounter a Berkshire couple hoping to rake in some offers on their multipurpose gardening tool. The Den then turns catwalk, witnessing a fashion show for an adaptive clothing range catering for a variety of disabilities. An app promising to reunite lost dogs with their owners pitches for additional investment, while a plant-based meal delivery service aims to get the Dragons' tastebuds tingling. Presented by Evan Davis.

programme.title: Coastal Defenders
programme.desc: Cargo in a British port grinds to a halt when a tugboat picks up a mystery object in its propeller. The divers respond to a callout to get the tug moving again, and end up using everything at their disposal - even a kitchen knife - in an attempt to free the propeller from whatever has been dumped in the river.

programme.title: Antiques Road Trip
programme.desc: Mark Hill buys a 1970s motorbike, has high hopes for a biscuit tin and sets his sights on auction glory with a stereoscopic viewer. Away from her purchasing, Irita Marriott takes a trip to an historic farm to find out why music played a key role in spreading the Salvation Army's message over the years. Later, the duo put friendship to one side as they enter the saleroom for a final time.

programme.title: The Hairy Bikers Go Local
programme.desc: Dave Myers and Si King visit the Stackpole Inn in Pembrokeshire, a multi award-winning gastro pub. Owners Gary and Becky first took it on 15 years ago, and were joined in 2019 by head chef Matt Waldron. It's the Bikers' mission to introduce Matt and team Stackpole to the fantastic local food producers that aren't yet on their radar.

programme.title: Yellowstone
programme.desc: Cameras follow as winter turns to spring in Yellowstone during 2016, capturing the re-emergence of a range of animals who leave their winter dens behind to explore the new, green world. programme.desc: Fiona Bruce presents as Penny Brittain explains how a valuable piece of porcelain was saved from being used for target practice, and a lucky visitor to the programme collects money earned in the show.

programme.desc: From Althorp in Northamptonshire, the home of the Spencer family, where Charles Hanson and Will Axon uncover movie memorabilia, including a photo signed by Charlie Chaplin, and a box of decorative Cartier studs. Paul Martin examines Althorp's collection of portrait paintings by renowned artist Joshua Reynolds.

programme.title: Richard Osman's House of Games
programme.desc: Mina Anwar, Glen Moore, Kiri Pritchard-McLean and Shaun Williamson go toe-to-toe testing their general knowledge skills in a variety of trivia-based games across the week.

programme.title: Coastal Defenders
programme.desc: A mooring structure on the Isle of Wight ferries is in desperate need of repair, bringing the entire terminal to a standstill. The dive team arrive to repair the seaworn structure, working day and night to get the job done on time, but the task is made worse when they come across a mountain of discarded rubbish ranging from teacups to prams.

programme.title: Back in Time for Birmingham
programme.desc: The Sharmas discover what life was like for South Asian families who settled in Britain in the past 70 years, beginning with getting a taste of the 1950s. Guiding them on their journey are BBC Asian Network presenter Noreen Khan and historian Yasmin Khan, whose own family members both migrated from Pakistan in the latter half of the 20th century. Mum Manisha and 20-year-old Alisha join the men at their lodgings, bringing home comforts and vital kitchen equipment.

programme.title: Great British Menu
programme.sub-title: London and South East - Starter and Fish
programme.desc: Chefs from London and the South East serve up their canapes, starters and fish dishes on an animation and illustration theme. Their vegan starters include a carrot dish paying tribute to Rabbit in Winnie the Pooh, a Gruffalo-inspired scrambled snake dish in an Indian street food style and a Caribbean green soup, similar to the one that the Clangers used to enjoy. Fish dishes include pan-fried halibut celebrating Pingu and a Filipino rhubarb sinigang broth paired with confit sea trout paying homage to Beatrix Potter's Jeremy Fisher.

programme.title: Predator: The Secret Scandal of J-Pop
programme.desc: Mobeen Azhar investigates the untold story of Japanese pop mogul Johnny Kitagawa and the allegations of sexual abuse against him by some of the boys in his talent agency. Despite the claims, the Japanese media has remained largely silent, even after the music mogul's death in 2019. Mobeen visits Japan to speak to those who say Kitagawa abused them, and find out how the allegations have affected his legacy.

programme.title: Parole
programme.desc: Forty-five-year-old Jon has been locked up for 19 years after violently robbing three students in 2004. A veteran of six previous parole hearings, he hopes an intense period of therapy has changed him enough for the board to give him a chance this time? Bethany, 23, breached her Criminal Behaviour Order in 2020 after repeatedly threatening to throw herself off motorway bridges, risking her own life and members of the public. Can she convince the board that she isn't a threat to herself or the public anymore?.

programme.desc: Gordon Ramsay heads to Arvada, Colorado, where a husband and wife have allowed their restaurant to fall into disrepair. Randy's hoarding is out of control, while Alexa, who runs the kitchen, has a lot to learn. To make matters worse, the Old Neighborhood is one of the filthiest eateries the fiery chef has ever seen, and only one of the biggest transformations of the series can save the business.

programme.title: Grand Designs
programme.desc: Kevin McCloud meets Audrey and Jeff Lovelock, who dream of living in one of west London's most exclusive areas. However, the only way they can afford it is to go underground. Their plan is to transform a listed Edwardian artist's studio - along with 5,000 square feet of derelict basement - into a bespoke subterranean home, complete with supersize kitchen, mezzanine sitting room, four en-suite bedrooms, a gym, cinema, steam room and wine cellar. As if the task was not tricky enough, they are doing it without proper architects' drawings and Audrey is project managing - and the difficulties begin almost from the start.

programme.title: Extraordinary Escapes with Sandi Toksvig
programme.desc: In Devon, Sandi is joined by comedian Sarah Millican to explore a Scandi-inspired architectural retreat ingeniously built into a hillside and tucked away in a small wood. In Lee Bay on the north coast, the pair stay in a 16th-century mill house dramatically positioned on the water's edge that is full of both history and surprises. Their final stop is Crowness Cleave where they enjoy a private spa retreat before experiencing the ultimate form of relaxation - a gong bath.

programme.title: George Clarke's Old House, New Home
programme.desc: The architect explores an arts and crafts-inspired house in Surrey. Built in the 1920s, it has tall chimneys, leaded windows, gabled ends and a steeply pitched roof. Sadly, it has Artex everywhere and incorporates some dubious design alterations. He sets out to help its owners turn it back into an elegant home for themselves and their three children. George also tackles a suburban home that has so many layers of wallpaper that peeling them back is like going back through a time warp.

programme.title: Parasite (2019)
programme.desc: A family living in poverty and getting by through an assortment of scams hatch a plan to infiltrate a wealthy household. They trick their way into assorted domestic staff jobs - ruthlessly ousting the established servants and devising ways of making their naive but self-centred employers' luxurious home their own. Oscar-winning South Korean satirical thriller, starring Kang-ho Song and Sun-kyun Lee. In Korean and English.

programme.title: Last Train from Gun Hill (1959)
programme.desc: A marshal discovers the man responsible for raping and killing his wife is actually the son of an old friend, setting the scene for a showdown. Western, starring Kirk Douglas, Anthony Quinn, Brian Hutton and Carolyn Jones.

programme.title: The Guns of Fort Petticoat (1957)
programme.desc: A lieutenant deserts after his commanding officer launches an unprovoked attack on a Comanche village during the Civil War. Realising that there are no soldiers in his home town to protect it from reprisals, he returns to train the local women to defend themselves. Western, starring Audie Murphy, Kathryn Grant, Hope Emerson and Jeff Donnell.

programme.title: Man of the West (1958)
programme.desc: Reformed outlaw Link is left stranded in the wilderness with a saloon singer and a conman for company when the train they are travelling on is robbed. By chance they stumble upon Link's old gang holed up in a shack, but his former partners in crime threaten violence against them unless Link agrees to take part in a bank robbery. Western, starring Gary Cooper, Lee J Cobb, Julie London and Arthur O'Connell.

programme.title: Billion Dollar Brain (1967)
programme.desc: Former secret agent Harry Palmer comes out of retirement to take a mysterious canister to Finland, and ends up embroiled in an American megalomaniac's bid to take over the world. Espionage thriller, directed by Ken Russell and starring Michael Caine, Oscar Homolka and Karl Malden.

programme.title: The Madness of King George (1994)
programme.desc: British monarch George III's behaviour becomes increasingly erratic, prompting fears that he is going insane. While physicians try to uncover the cause of his condition, the king's enemies in Parliament and the frustrated Prince of Wales conspire to have him declared insane and removed from the throne. Period drama based on Alan Bennett's play, starring Nigel Hawthorne, Helen Mirren and Rupert Everett.

programme.title: The Godfather Part II (1974)
programme.desc: Mafia don Michael Corleone sets out to clinch a make-or-break deal with an ageing gangster - but his plans are blown apart by a traitor within the family. Michael's story is intercut with flashback sequences chronicling the early life of his father Vito, as he makes the shift from immigrant grocery-store clerk to Mob kingpin. Francis Ford Coppola's Oscar-winning crime drama sequel, with Al Pacino, Robert De Niro, Robert Duvall, Diane Keaton, Talia Shire, John Cazale, Michael V Gazzo and Lee Strasberg.

programme.sub-title: River Cottage: Winter's on the Way
programme.desc: Hugh Fearnley-Whittingstall returns to celebrate the selection of fare available over the autumn and winter seasons. programme.title: The Great British Bake Off
programme.desc: The 10 remaining amateur cooks' tart-making abilities are put to the test in the third round of the competition. Their first task is to bake a tarte Tatin, with judges Paul Hollywood and Mary Berry looking for intriguing flavour combinations to tickle their tastebuds. The hopefuls then face another daunting technical challenge as they try to replicate Mary's seemingly straightforward recipe for treacle tart, but the delicate task of adding a lattice top leaves some contestants flummoxed. Finally, they try to create an ornate fruit tart fit for gracing the window display of a leading patisserie - before discovering the identities of the latest Star Baker and the person who will be heading home. Presented by Mel Giedroyc and Sue Perkins. From 2012.

programme.title: The Great British Bake Off
programme.desc: Judges Mary Berry and Paul Hollywood assess the remaining contestants' dessert-making skills. The hopefuls start by creating tortes before tackling this week's technical test - the delicate French dish of creme caramel. Though these two rounds provide a stern examination of the amateurs' creative flair and technical ability, they then face possibly the toughest task of the series so far - a six-hour challenge to create a show-stopping layered meringue. Once the sugar has set, who will be this week's Star Baker, and who will be going home? Presented by Mel Giedroyc and Sue Perkins. From 2012.

programme.desc: The 10 remaining amateur cooks' tart-making abilities are put to the test in the third round of the competition. Their first task is to bake a tarte Tatin, with judges Paul Hollywood and Mary Berry looking for intriguing flavour combinations to tickle their tastebuds. programme.title: The Great British Bake Off
programme.desc: Judges Mary Berry and Paul Hollywood assess the remaining contestants' dessert-making skills. The hopefuls start by creating tortes before tackling this week's technical test - the delicate French dish of creme caramel. programme.title: Four in a Bed
